<h1>@HI{{keredomo}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @Splain{{}} <strong>@HI{{keredomo}}</strong>
<li> @Vru{{}} <strong>@HI{{keredomo}}</strong>
<li> @Vta{{}} <strong>@HI{{keredomo}}</strong>
<li> @Ai{{}} <strong>@HI{{keredomo}}</strong>
<li> @Anastem{{}}@HI{{da}} <strong>@HI{{keredomo}}</strong>
<li> @N{{}}@HI{{da}} <strong>@HI{{keredomo}}</strong>
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{keredomo}}</strong> is a isjunctive subordinate conjunction that joins two sentences.
the basic meaning is "although."

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{bamboo^inside}}san'ni@KJ{{electricity^tale}}wokaketa<strong>keredo</strong>
      @KJ{{detain^guard}}deshita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I phoned Takeuchi but she was out.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{kono@KJ{{book}}ha@KJ{{tall}}i<strong>keredomo</strong>ii@KJ{{book}}desu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Although this book is expensive, it's a good book.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>
</p>

<p>
At the end of a sentence <strong>@HI{{keredomo}}</strong> implies something exists that qualifies what is actually said.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{tamaniha@KJ{{trip^going}}nimo@KJ{{going}}kitaito@KJ{{think}}tteirundesu<strong>kedo</strong>.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I'd really like to go on a trip once in a while (but I don't have the time).
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{keredomo}}</strong> can be used to delimit a preliminary remark.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{mada@KJ{{departure^shoot}}made1@KJ{{time^interval}}mouarimasu<strong>kedo</strong>,
      doushimashouka.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      There's still an hour until the departure, so what shall we do?
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
Another usage of <strong>@HI{{keredomo}}</strong> at the end of a sentence is to emphasise that the speaker
wants things to turn out as stated.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{early}}ku@KJ{{warmth}}kakunarutoiinda<strong>kedo</strong>.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      It would be nice if it got warm soon.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
In @S1{{}}<strong>@HI{{keredomo}}</strong>@S2{{}}, @S1{{}} is a subordinate clause and is usually in the plain form.
However, in very polite speech @S1{{}} can be in the polite form.
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{keredomo}}</strong> has a number of informal forms. In decreasing order of formality
these are @HI{{keredo}}, @HI{{kedomo}} and @HI{{kedo}}.
</p>

